00:00:19.140 --> 00:00:21.300
how do you find Containers useful?

00:00:21.300 --> 00:00:24.480
Yeah. Well, I think the Shipping Container or

00:00:24.480 --> 00:00:27.435
Analogy of Containers is

00:00:27.434 --> 00:00:31.320
really the best way to understand how Containers make our life easier.

00:00:31.320 --> 00:00:33.914
Before there were Shipping Containers,

00:00:33.914 --> 00:00:37.519
it was very difficult to move things around the World versus now we can put

00:00:37.520 --> 00:00:41.630
everything in a nice little box and because they're all in the same box,

00:00:41.630 --> 00:00:45.240
we can attach them to a truck and drive them to a Shipyard

00:00:45.240 --> 00:00:49.505
and put them on a Ship or put them on a big boat.

00:00:49.505 --> 00:00:52.490
We can build big expensive tools,

00:00:52.490 --> 00:00:54.440
Cranes to move these boxes around,

00:00:54.439 --> 00:00:57.210
pick them up and put them different places.

00:00:57.820 --> 00:01:01.365
That's how Containers makes our life better.

00:01:01.365 --> 00:01:05.180
Everything becomes the same and we can develop tooling around that sameness.

00:01:05.180 --> 00:01:08.200
So, you're saying that using Containers

00:01:08.200 --> 00:01:11.689
in Software is similar to our Shipping Container Analogy?

00:01:11.689 --> 00:01:12.614
Yeah, yeah.

00:01:12.614 --> 00:01:14.959
It just makes life easier because you can have

00:01:14.959 --> 00:01:18.969
these tools that are developed for a specific Container,

00:01:18.969 --> 00:01:20.819
but it doesn't really matter what's in the Container,

00:01:20.819 --> 00:01:23.679
like it doesn't matter what Software we're running underneath?

00:01:23.680 --> 00:01:25.760
That's right Jennifer.

00:01:27.090 --> 00:01:30.890
